<section id="integrated-labels">
  <header>
    <h2>Integrated labels</h2>
  </header>

  <p><strong>Integrated labels</strong> keep labels inside the field boundary, preserving context even after someone starts typing. They reduce vertical height, work well in dense UIs, and keep the label present so the input’s purpose never disappears once the placeholder is replaced with real content.</p>
  
  <p>Use this pattern for short inputs like email, passwords, or URLs when space is tight. Keep motion minimal: labels should lift or shrink smoothly without obscuring typed text, and placeholder copy should remain concise so the control still reads as an input rather than a button.</p>

	<div class="section-example">
		<form action="">
			
			<div class="integrated-label">
				<input type="email" id="email-address" placeholder="Email address">      
				<label for="email-address">Email address</label>
			</div>

			<div class="integrated-label">
				<input type="password" id="new-password" placeholder="Password">
				<label for="new-password">Password</label>
			</div>

			<div class="integrated-label">
				<input type="url" id="website-name" placeholder="Website name">
				<label for="website-name">Website name</label>
			</div>
		</form>
	</div>

  <p class="note"><strong>Clarity over flair:</strong> ensure the resting label has sufficient contrast, and that the floating state leaves enough room for long translations. Never rely on placeholder text to convey requirements; the persistent label and any helper text should carry the meaning for screen readers and speech-to-text users.</p>


  <div class="code-example">
    <pre><code class="html">&lt;div class="integrated-label"&gt;
  &lt;input type="..." id="..."   placeholder="..."&gt;
  &lt;label for="..."&gt;...&lt;/label&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>
  
  </div>
</section>



